2 HOUSE BILL 523
1 Annotated Code of Maryland
2 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
3 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
4 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
5 Article – Real Property
6 7–105.1.
7 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
8 (8) “Owner–occupied residential property” means residential property in
9 which at least one unit is occupied by an individual who:
10 (i) Has an ownership interest in the property; and
11 (ii) Uses the property as the individual’s primary residence.
12 (12) “Residential property” means real property improved by four or fewer
13 single family dwelling units that are designed principally and are intended for human
14 habitation.
15 (b) (1) Except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection, an action to
16 foreclose a mortgage or deed of trust on residential property may not be filed until the later
17 of:
18 (i) 90 days after a default in a condition on which the mortgage or
19 deed of trust provides that a sale may be made; or
20 (ii) 45 days after the notice of intent to foreclose required under
21 subsection (c) of this section is sent.
22 (2) (i) The secured party may petition the circuit court for leave to
23 immediately commence an action to foreclose the mortgage or deed of trust if:
24 1. The loan secured by the mortgage or deed of trust was
25 obtained by fraud or deception;
26 2. No payments have ever been made on the loan secured by
27 the mortgage or deed of trust;
28 3. The property subject to the mortgage or deed of trust has
29 been destroyed;
30 4. The default occurred after the stay has been lifted in a
31 bankruptcy proceeding; or

HOUSE BILL 523 3
1 5. The property subject to the mortgage or deed of trust is
2 property that is vacant and abandoned as provided under § 7–105.18 of this subtitle.
3 (ii) The court may rule on the petition with or without a hearing.
4 (iii) If the petition is granted:
5 1. The action may be filed at any time after a default in a
6 condition on which the mortgage or deed of trust provides that a sale may be made; and
7 2. The secured party need not send the written notice of
8 intent to foreclose required under subsection (c) of this section.
9 (e) An order to docket or a complaint to foreclose a mortgage or deed of trust on
10 residential property shall:
11 (1) Include:
12 (i) If applicable, the license number of:
13 1. The mortgage originator; and
14 2. The mortgage lender; and
15 (ii) An affidavit stating:
16 1. The date on which the default occurred and the nature of
17 the default; and
18 2. If applicable, that:
19 A. A notice of intent to foreclose was sent to the mortgagor or
20 grantor in accordance with subsection (c) of this section and the date on which the notice
21 was sent; and
22 B. At the time the notice of intent to foreclose was sent, the
23 contents of the notice of intent to foreclose were accurate; [and]
24 (2) Be accompanied by:
25 (i) The original or a certified copy of the mortgage or deed of trust;
26 (ii) A statement of the debt remaining due and payable supported by
27 an affidavit of the plaintiff or the secured party or the agent or attorney of the plaintiff or
28 secured party;

4 HOUSE BILL 523
1 (iii) A copy of the debt instrument accompanied by an affidavit
2 certifying ownership of the debt instrument;
3 (iv) If applicable, the original or a certified copy of the assignment of
4 the mortgage for purposes of foreclosure or the deed of appointment of a substitute trustee;
5 (v) If any defendant is an individual, an affidavit that is in
6 compliance with § 521 of the Servicemembers Civil Relief Act, 50 U.S.C. App. § 501 et seq.;
7 (vi) If applicable, a copy of the notice of intent to foreclose;
8 (vii) If the secured party and mortgagor or grantor have elected to
9 participate in prefile mediation, the report of the prefile mediation issued by the Office of
10 Administrative Hearings;
11 (viii) If the secured party and the mortgagor or grantor have not
12 elected to participate in prefile mediation, a statement that the parties have not elected to
13 participate in prefile mediation;
14 (ix) In addition to any other filing fees required by law, a filing fee in
15 the amount of $450; and
16 (x) 1. If the loss mitigation analysis has been completed subject
17 to subsection (g) of this section, a final loss mitigation affidavit in the form prescribed by
18 regulation adopted by the Commissioner of Financial Regulation; and
19 2. If the loss mitigation analysis has not been completed, a
20 preliminary loss mitigation affidavit in the form prescribed by regulation adopted by the
21 Commissioner of Financial Regulation; AND
22 (3) BE COMMENCED NOT LATER THAN 10 YEARS AFTER THE DATE OF
23 DEFAULT CLAIMED IN THE ORDER TO DOCKET OR COMPLAINT TO FORECLOSE THE
24 DATE OF THE LAST PAYMENT.
25 (E–1) IF A FORECLOSURE IS COMMENCED BY A SECURED PARTY THAT
26 ACQUIRED DEBT THAT WAS IN DEFAULT FOR 5 OR MORE YEARS BEFORE THE
27 ACQUISITION, THE SECURED PARTY SHALL PRESENT THE DOCUMENTS REQUIRED
28 UNDER § 5–1203(B) OF THE COURTS ARTICLE WITH THE ORDER TO DOCKET OR
29 COMPLAINT TO FORECLOSE.
30 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
31 1, 2026.

